commit_message:
Fixed long log messages

Fixed cutting of long log messages and added some additional
messages. Increased sleep time after creating partitions in
order to give udev more time to create partition devices.

Closes-Bug: #1318747
Change-Id: I9dfa9522213354d2888ad21c384774b920a11275

commit_message:
Edits on Security Guide

Better follow conventions, especially:
* remove Latinism like via and i.e.
* use variable lists
* Add missing <filename>
* wrap long lines

Change-Id: I2a537df78ddf4fbeb127b058bf05caaf42441d5f

Add spec for bp:post-run-cleanup

This patch adds a spec file for enhancing tempest cleanup blueprint.

Fixed many reStructuredText formatting errors, new to this markup.

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow

Additional configuration options in neutron.conf added for enhanced
customization.  Implemented so that if none of the configurable
options are set, the result will match the 'minimum' configuration
necessary.

Added creation of the /var/log/neutron directory and appropriate
permission setting to the neutron-source-install.

Change-Id: I8fdad2b0f27026c37a9261a4a11ff955d9a729f1
"}]
commit_message:
Add configuration options for Neutron

Additional configuration options in neutron.conf added for enhanced
customization.  Implemented so that if none of the configurable
options are set, the result will match the 'minimum' configuration
necessary.

Added creation of the /var/log/neutron directory and appropriate
permission setting to the neutron-source-install.

Change-Id: I8fdad2b0f27026c37a9261a4a11ff955d9a729f1

(2 comments)

Improve service_get_all in nova.compute.api

Make nova.compute.api to return a List object

Move the services filtering to the db

Change-Id: I267b816a60651c115d7576242f8922c2b6cce056
Closes-Bug: #1294853

commit_message:
Add a helper tool which clears zookeeper test dirs

Create a tool that can clear any leftover garbage left
by the testing of taskflow unit tests with zookeeper for
when this is needed (for example, a test does not clean up
correctly on its own).

Change-Id: Icfaf28273b76a6ca27683d174f111fba2858f055

commit_message:
Add Power params for undercloud ssh access

Without correct PowerUserName nova pxe_ssh driver cant
boot vm.

Added params to undercloud environment:
- PowerUserName
- PowerHost
- PowerManager

Closes-Bug: #1319034
Change-Id: I0a51221880de968e775c0a377f539a3453828b48

commit_message:
Use HOT instead of CFN heat template format

New Heaet features will get added to HOT but possibly not the
older CFN format, and it's easier to make the change now than
later.

The only code change is in heat_stack to look for 'resources'
instead of 'Resources'; all other changes are to the Heat template
sections within PL class definitions. Keys are lower-cased and
in some cases changed to match HOT (e.g. key_name instead of KeyName),
and sections specifying Heat resources add heat_template_version to
the template.

Implements blueprint replace-cfn-templates-with-hot

Change-Id: If4d34cd25a4e964d7555fedf218512d5c0f5615c

commit_message:
Enable passing several FQNs as one field's type

These types should be specified as string (no YAML sequences!), string
entities are separated with ', '.  It is a kind of workaround until
descendants of some abstract MuranoPL class given by its FQN cannot be
calculated by murano-api - so we have to provide them explicitly. But
even after that issue is fixed, the client-side code can be reused.

Change-Id: I0cbf26b8fd6834378943a600abf98372d45f1788

commit_message:
debug level logs should not be translated

According to the OpenStack translation policy available at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards debug messages
should not be translated. Like mentioned in several changes in
Nova by garyk this is to help prioritize log translation.

Change-Id: Idd917acd97481d6b644e307adb002354b37f34a1

commit_message:
Simplify field-level validators evaluation

Field-level validator should depend only on field's value as its data,
so it doesn't need complicated logic for retrieving all form's data.

Change-Id: I669328f1719f5038c60fd9afd2f5c794b2bf0e1d

commit_message:
debug level logs should not be translated

According to the OpenStack translation policy available at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards debug messages
should not be translated. Like mentioned in several changes in
Nova by garyk this is to help prioritize log translation.

Change-Id: I082f925e6923613e1e8cfeb5a0533747087a5e02

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-09 13:17:49.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor yumdownloader conflicts detection

On the modern OSes (like Ubuntu-13.10 or CentOS-6) the following
commands return nothing:

  yumdownloader -q --resolve ... > yumdownloader.log
  grep "has depsolving problems" yumdownloader.log

Which breaks our conflicts detections mechanism during ISO build.

Change-Id: I67e4eefaba4340f84730515e59a806adba184af1
'}, {'created': '2014-04-23 07:39:24.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor yumdownloader conflicts detection

On the modern OSes (like Ubuntu-13.10 or CentOS-6) the following
commands return nothing:

  yumdownloader -q --resolve ... > yumdownloader.log
  grep "has depsolving problems" yumdownloader.log

Which breaks our conflicts detections mechanism during ISO build.

Change-Id: I67e4eefaba4340f84730515e59a806adba184af1

On the modern OSes (like Ubuntu-13.10 or CentOS-6) the following

commit_message:
Refactor yumdownloader conflicts detection

On the modern OSes (like Ubuntu-13.10 or CentOS-6) the following
commands return nothing:

  yumdownloader -q --resolve ... > yumdownloader.log
  grep "has depsolving problems" yumdownloader.log

Which breaks our conflicts detections mechanism during ISO build.

Change-Id: I67e4eefaba4340f84730515e59a806adba184af1

commit_message:
Put version.yaml into /etc/fuel/$RELEASE/ dir

During master provisioning create /etc/fuel/5.0 directory, add
version.yaml and make symlink from /etc/fuel/5.0/version.yaml to
/etc/fuel/version.yaml

Change-Id: Ie9080720c60e29e43f3e858f40b25c60a5183423
Closes-Bug: #1317049
Implements: blueprint fuel-containerization-of-services

commit_message:
Log a cause of db backend connection failure

If opportunistic test case, i.e. fixture, can't connect to a test
database, it is happening silently, without any logs. Most of times we
need to know a cause of fall.

Change-Id: I328d52d95321b9fabb714b9e4316fa65f4ac9732
Closes-Bug: #1306017

commit_message:
Opportunistic migration tests

Migrations should be tested with real database backends. For this goal
intended number of base test cases which used in current implementation.
Previously there were two ways to run migration tests: using
opportunistic test cases (default way we've been using on CI) and
by using database connection strings, specified in test_migrations.conf,
for every particular database test case. For the sake of simplicity and
consistency we are moving to using of opportunistic db test cases here.

Change-Id: I92b1dcd830c4755f429a0f6529911e607c2c7de7

[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the test using in-file SQLite database

SQLite in-file uses exclusively lock for database, so the connection
must be only one.

Change-Id: I9aad455d1466e4b17579253af47bf1b7e51dbc49
Closes-Bug: #1308032
'}, {'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the test using in-file SQLite database

SQLite in-file uses exclusively lock for database, so the connection
must be only one.

Change-Id: I9aad455d1466e4b17579253af47bf1b7e51dbc49
Closes-Bug: #1308032
'}, {'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Single engine connection

SQLite in file provides engine with NullPull, which can have only single
connection, in accordance with SQLite concurrency rules. Opportunistic
test cases could provide SQLite in file engine instances. We should use
only single connection in every method or function which uses database
connections to prevent queries to a locked database.

Change-Id: I9aad455d1466e4b17579253af47bf1b7e51dbc49
ClosesBug: #1308032
'}]
commit_message:
Fix the test using in-file SQLite database

SQLite in-file uses exclusively lock for database, so the connection
must be only one.

Change-Id: I9aad455d1466e4b17579253af47bf1b7e51dbc49
Closes-Bug: #1308032

commit_message:
autohelp.py: update the paramters handling

- generate the tables in the doc/common/tables dir by default
- make the -i switch optional, and assume that git git repositories are
  in a ./sources/ dir
- use elif's instead of multiple return statements in the subcommand
  test

Change-Id: If96ac9df247cea5061c056328307ec88ab74a4f3

[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "Fix migrations changing the type of deleted column

SQLite doesn't provide a native implementation of BOOLEAN data type.
SQLAlchemy emulates BOOLEAN data type for SQLite using INT column +
CHECK constraint.
We have a few migrations changing the type of column 'deleted' from
BOOLEAN to INT. Due to limitations of ALTER in SQLite, in order to do
that, we omit the original 'deleted' column as well as the corresponding
CHECK constraint when recreating the table. Omitting of the constraint
is more tricky. It's implemented by analyzing the SQL text used for its
rendering. SQLAlchemy versions 0.8.3+ slightly changed the way
constraints are rendered, so we have to update our migrations changing
the type of 'deleted' column to work with SQLAlchemy 0.8.3+ on SQLite
backend (we aren't using SQLite in production, but we still need it for
running of unit tests).

Change-Id: I60b619f79831b4a6d1b83622b936fb792721d516
Closes-Bug: #1252693

commit_message:
Fix migrations changing the type of deleted column

SQLite doesn't provide a native implementation of BOOLEAN data type.
SQLAlchemy emulates BOOLEAN data type for SQLite using INT column +
CHECK constraint.
We have a few migrations changing the type of column 'deleted' from
BOOLEAN to INT. Due to limitations of ALTER in SQLite, in order to do
that, we omit the original 'deleted' column as well as the corresponding
CHECK constraint when recreating the table. Omitting of the constraint
is more tricky. It's implemented by analyzing the SQL text used for its
rendering. SQLAlchemy versions 0.8.3+ slightly changed the way
constraints are rendered, so we have to update our migrations changing
the type of 'deleted' column to work with SQLAlchemy 0.8.3+ on SQLite
backend (we aren't using SQLite in production, but we still need it for
running of unit tests).

Change-Id: I60b619f79831b4a6d1b83622b936fb792721d516
Closes-Bug: #1252693

commit_message:
Send sighup to rsyslogd

After remove_nodes action, create mcollecte client
with execute_shell_command plugin for master node, and perform:

ssh root@#{master_ip} 'pkill -HUP rsyslogd'

Change-Id: I8ab764aaa3bceb9c08c99d5bfe08582c83e267c7
Closes-Bug: #1315382

commit_message:
Add master_ip to engine parameter section

master_ip should be passed for every task where rebooting is involved
therefore it is convenient to place them in engine section

Sending kill -HUP to rsyslogd required after removing nodes
to refresh its configuration

Change-Id: Ibd3882621380da1d5fcdb15397438f554b3619c7
Related-Bug: #1315382

Add a base test case that allows to check if the DB schema obtained
by applying of migration scripts is equal to the one produced from
models definitions. It's very important that those two stay in sync
to be able to use models definitions for generation of the initial
DB schema. Though, due to the using of sqlalchemy-migrate (since we
had to write migration scripts manually and alembic can generate
them automatically) we have many divergences in projects right now,
which must be detected and fixed.

of schema comparison instead of writing our own tools.

commit_message:
Add a base test case for DB schema comparison

Add a base test case that allows to check if the DB schema obtained
by applying of migration scripts is equal to the one produced from
models definitions. It's very important that those two stay in sync
to be able to use models definitions for generation of the initial
DB schema. Though, due to the using of sqlalchemy-migrate (since we
had to write migration scripts manually and alembic can generate
them automatically) we have many divergences in projects right now,
which must be detected and fixed.
Fortunately, we can now rely on alembic + sqlalchemy implementation
of schema comparison instead of writing our own tools.

Mirrored from: I0758c7e09d1d46ce870c3f94f76c2a177955e143
Blueprint: sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: Ie384a7f895ac25b20ef86ceffb1841ab33f6cdbe

commit_message:
Reuse exceptions from Oslo

- Remove unused exceptions from novaclient.exceptions
- Reuse exceptions from common code

OpenStack clients which already use exception from common code:
- ironicclient   - I784007f36dd6a63fc4c77e0d0f0f000e05eb792f
- keystoneclient - Iedf4e5d753d4278d81751ba0f55fdef3566b56de
- saharaclient
- tuskarclient   - Iacbf219168fae62d864c6594dd41e0737e848cfa

Similar patches in other clients related to reusing exceptions
from common code:
- cinderclient   - I07f04ba5357e0196fe43b510e1d2fff5afa02faa
- glanceclient   - I9838391cff7e450f08d27668564b02e63259186c

Related to blueprint common-client-library-2

Change-Id: Ia35d65d57a0047f88a609070f8b4c76215cbd3e9

commit_message:
Check requested image size

Add a sanity check to the prepare() method in the PXE driver to check
if check if the requested image to be deployed is larger than the root
partition size.

Closes-Bug: #1288007
Change-Id: I5d80b147a330aee2df237b4a1b82e2c6e990f148

commit_message:
Allowed background creation of service VM with share creation

This is required before implementation of 'volume-type-support' bp,
where service VMs will be created on backend before first share creation.

Change-Id: Idfd45cba6c14cfe37902af6474b79ec76f77fc68

I think what lifeless was alluding to is that 	UNDERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG isn't necessary at all.

ENV_JSON is read from undercloud-env.json, so rather than setting yet another env var, a user can put their extra config into there. This is nice in that it avoids env var proliferation and we could eventually migrate the other env vars in there.

However, it gets a bit awkward because ExtraConfig is generally going to be a string of JSON, with lots of escaped double quotes. That's nasty to write so it'd be much better to support EG undercloud-extraconfig.json which is merged by devtest_undercloud.sh into ENV_JSON.

Alternatively, we could accept that ExtraConfig is a bit special because it's a string of JSON and allow it an env var, while still pushing simple values currently held in env vars into undercloud-env.json.

Finally - there's a consistency issue between undercloud and overcloud here. Whichever approach is taken should be applied to overcloud as well (IMO in the same patch).

lifeless please arbitrate?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-09 15:28:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

commit_message:
Expose passthrough configuration in undercloud.

Since the point of passthrough configuration is to let users use it,
we probably need to expose it :).

Relates to: I4ab7014187cf6e346448353a6c4799999061a36a

Change-Id: Iedf75048a452b129ca2d9fdc3bd97b0745cf6549

commit_message:
Allows user-specified PXE timeout for undercloud

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/86523/2 makes the PXE deploy timeout
into a configurable value.  This patch allows the user to specify that
value, and depends on the other one being merged first, as well as the
dependent patch in tripleo-incubator.

Change-Id: Idafe1b2464d925962b3986c6ae982586925a0122
Co-Author: matthew.gilliard@hp.com

commit_message:
Fix getting human_id attribute with None resource name

When getting resource's human_id attribute with the resource name is None,
it will raise "TypeError" while safe decoding the human_id.
This situation will occur when booting an instance with image name and
there is image without name in our environment.

Change-Id: I76330ad96871a89339e427f8ef52f3176e7cfecc
Closes-bug: #1318446

commit_message:
Use lrzip+tar instead of lrzuntar

Extract docker images from archive using lrzip + tar instead of
single lrzuntar command. It should lower extraction times on a
weak hardware.

Also remove each container tarball right after loading it into
docker in order to reduce disk usage.

Change-Id: I27a109d8e4c3925b53553f6ac86802111ee404b1

This might solve 99%+ percentage of this issue, but I am wondering following scenaio:
In database concept, if you query , you get read lock, if you update , you get write lock
so if Thread A query ,then thread B query, then A update, then thread B update

it might lead to problem

+1 for with_lockmode'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2014-03-06 08:35:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

got those comments from db/sqlalchemy/session.py
 

Avoid ``with_lockmode('UPDATE')`` when possible.

  In MySQL/InnoDB, when a ``SELECT ... FOR UPDATE`` query does not match
  any rows, it will take a gap-lock. This is a form of write-lock on the
  "gap" where no rows exist, and prevents any other writes to that space.
  This can effectively prevent any INSERT into a table by locking the gap
  at the end of the index. Similar problems will occur if the SELECT FOR UPDATE
  has an overly broad WHERE clause, or doesn't properly use an index.

  One idea proposed at ODS Fall '12 was to use a normal SELECT to test the
  number of rows matching a query, and if only one row is returned,
  then issue the SELECT FOR UPDATE.'}, {'account_id': 6062, 'date': '2014-03-07 10:57:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-07 10:57:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-03-04 09:22:52.000000000', 'message': "Add lock on API layer delete floating IP

There are potential race condition when multiple nova-api
service is running. We need to prevent the concurrent access to
the same floating ip, though db layer function is ok for floating
ip, the quota will be released more than one time and it will
lead to potential problem later

There is another possible solution: check whether the db is
*really* updated with the value we want, which means the second
operation will fail with some exception like 'FloatingIPAlreadyUpdate'
but it will need db layer support and current solution will

commit_message:
Add lock on API layer delete floating IP

There are potential race condition when multiple nova-api
service is running. We need to prevent the concurrent access to
the same floating ip, though db layer function is ok for floating
ip, the quota will be released more than one time and it will
lead to potential problem later

So the solution: check whether the db is *really* updated with the
value we want, which means the second operation will fail and
return None, so network api layer can handle it

Change-Id: I028938a4c387d21a8880ae168b161a763e7361ff
Closes-Bug: #1268569

commit_message:
Py3: Use bytes more consistently for HTTP bodies

This is needed to get glanceclient working on Python3. This work is far from
done, and only a handful more tests now pass, but progress!

Change-Id: I463eafa4142b4530f56db65c47b35a582e3ff5e5

commit_message:
Add "." for help strings

The command descriptions did not include a "." at the end but the
argument description does. Add "." everywhere.

Also capitalize and add "." for parameter of capabilities.

Change-Id: I2355e0d0c38170d669c8e568361faf4b68203d16

Fix the dot overlaps with the table border in Availability Zones table

Zones table.

commit_message:
Fix security group list when not defined for an instance

If an instance has an empty security group list an exception
is thrown due to iteration attempt of None.

To fix this, this patch modifies get_instance_security_group
to return an empty list instead of None.

Change-Id: I7efb3c3a58d7e20501d126c6d194479ca1d14166
Closes-Bug: #1291489

commit_message:
Fix RESP if NoValidHost raised when nova resize

When run nova resize, nova scheduler will raise NoValidHost exception
if there is not enough resource available on any compute node.
Then nova conductor will catch the exception and report Warning message.
However, nova api does not catch exception but responds with a 202 Accepted.

Change-Id: I917f201ab29f82c608649b2350ce46b3778dce82
Fixes: bug #1314015

commit_message:
Add EventReporter for rebuild instance (get_image)

There is a EventReport for get_image in shelve operation (conductor)
We need to report this event to user for them to get more information,
so add this event in rebuild operation.

Change-Id: I79b578a3d5b89b90ccc2b656527249d8e89310a6

commit_message:
Handle non-referenced and duplicated files

Admin Guide/Training Guides:
* section_rootwrap.xml was renamed to
  compute/section-compute-rootwrap.xml in change
  Ie300a9ce25d305b80bb0b21d3cfc318909f3a123. The file is unused and
  duplicated now, remove it.
* section_object-storage-admin.xml and
  common/section_objectstorage_tenant-specific-image-storage.xml
  were not referenced anywhere, add them to ch_objectstorage.xml.
* files common/section_objectstorage-account-reaper has the comment:
  "Old module003-ch008-account-reaper edited, renamed, and
  stored in doc/common for use by both Cloud Admin and
  Operator Training Guides..." - make it as suggested.
  There were more files moved the same way, update training-guides to
  use the new files and remove duplicates files.
  Also, remove comment from the lines, we have git for history, no need
  to duplicate the information.

Config Reference:
* Object Storage:
  - Add new "Container sync realms configuration" section and add tables.
  - Include file common/tables/swift-proxy-server-filter-container_sync.xml.
* Identity:
  - Include file common/tables/keystone-auth_token.xml

Change-Id: I6c8f41a01815485904c48db0695deb7813634df1

commit_message:
Adding Keystone protection with RBAC

Admin guide was missing Keystone API protection with Role Based Access
Control
(RBAC).
This patch gets the information from Keystone configuration.rst

Change-Id: I7609452ef6ca8ddbaefaecaa305561fab8564252
Closes-bug: 1279486

commit_message:
Better follow conventions in HA Guide

Follow our conventions for title capitalization and usage of
project/service names.

Follow conventions on using active voice, no -ing for titles.

Co-Authored-By: Diane Fleming <diane.fleming@rackspace.com>

Change-Id: I05e368f8dda436454d2daca1a6775105032a39fc
Partial-Bug: #1217503

commit_message:
Make port-id and net-id keys mutually exclusive

These keys are never used together, and port-id always takes precedence
in Nova API when present. This patch makes these parameters mutually
exclusive and updates help strings accordingly.

Change-Id: I207dc637cb69d9ab3ff6024a657d2c1890057b4d
Closes-Bug: #1314097

commit_message:
Change parameters of add_timestamp in ComputeDriverCPUMonitor class

Change parameter 'cls' to 'self' in wrapper. 'cls' may mislead developpers
that this decorator returns a classmethod. Use functools.wraps to follow
the common pattern of decorator in nova.

closes-bug: #1288281

Change-Id: I6acbcba7297607dc6d07e8668ad07e6ca81d4456

'}, {'created': '2014-05-06 00:37:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add extension-list command for v3 API

one of v3 API.

Note:
The command name of v2 is "nova list-extensions" but the one of v3,
which this patch adds, is "nova extension-list" because the name fits
to the other command names.

Change-Id: Ibee712b0aa5898a94e362f20be71e8863500b195

The command name of v2 is "nova list-extensions" but the one of v3,
which this patch adds, is "nova extension-list" because the name fits
to the other command names.

Change-Id: Ibee712b0aa5898a94e362f20be71e8863500b195
'}]
commit_message:
Add extension-list command for v3 API

Nova returns available extension list through its REST API.
The command of v2 API has been implemented, and this patch adds the
one of v3 API.

Note:
The command name of v2 is "nova list-extensions" but the one of v3,
which this patch adds, is "nova extension-list" because the name fits
to the other command names.

Change-Id: Ibee712b0aa5898a94e362f20be71e8863500b195

commit_message:
TestRandomString was calling the wrong setUp

Just incorrect usage of super(). This was bypassing HeatTestCase.setUp()
and causing extra logs to be printed.

Change-Id: I6f77cce53b971b14637e8705c3f73993ac458550
Partial-bug: 1281226

commit_message:
Make Server metadata a passive store again

This change reverts the software deployments change which polls
the deployments API whenever a Server resource metadata is read.

The Server metadata has reverted to being a standard resource
metadata store, and the deployments are pushed into this metadata
directly in the database whenever the deployments API is used to
create or update a deployment.

As part of the effort to not require a Stack.load for polling metadata
this change is for
Partial-Bug: #1306743

Change-Id: Ib461e1bab816d4b9e332786004c53a2f73d773e8

commit_message:
Add a register-nodes command and associated API

As a first step of making register-nodes cleverer, port it from shell
to Python, making use of the subprocess module to call nova or ironic.
This slightly changes the interface, in that ironic usage is detected
via Keystone, rather than use of an environment variable. As an added
bonus, it is also tested and documented.

Change-Id: I0d9ef1b3f19c55ed5b696871303a66808c3cf658

commit_message:
Resolve pep8 import issues

* H301 one import per line
* H302 import only modules
* H306  imports not in alphabetical order

Change-Id: I75d6f63515b6f5d6dc92d8cafd2176e0415c23f5

commit_message:
debug level logs should not be translated

According to the OpenStack translation policy available at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards debug messages
should not be translated. Like mentioned in several changes in
Nova by garyk this is to help prioritize log translation.

Change-Id: I7fa02c78d0c6b1642db7365b6131fb9aa73dee75

commit_message:
Add benchmark for tempest. Part 2

Several new scenarios added in tempest benchmark:

* scenario for launching all tests

* scenario for launching all tests from given set(special set_name
validator was added for this scenario)

* scenario for launching all tests from given list of test names
(Also, test coverage for validator `tempest_tests_exists` was increased
for situations like in this scenario)

* scenario for launching all tests which match given regex expression

bp benchmark-scenarios-based-on-tempest

Change-Id: I3e715cb360dec3d5d8683a9001c4f2221b49d1ac

I don't like the recommendations and we already discussed that in the past (I don't remember where, maybe on the SUSE Cloud ML). The result: use --no-recommends if you don't want to install recommend packages. But I think using --no-recommends should be documented, because you don't need (for example) rabbitmq and couchdb on the Compute node.

You can used every changed zypper call as an example.

zypper install openstack-neutron-openvswitch-agent

This also installs couchdb and rabbitmq-server. That's not necessary and that's (my point of view) not expected.

zypper install openstack-nova-compute kvm openstack-utils

This also installs couchdb and rabbitmq-server. That's not necessary and that's (my point of view) not expected."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-05-07 19:28:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I just tested (I have neither rabbitmq-server nor couchdb installed):
# zypper install openstack-neutron-openvswitch-agent

The following 10 NEW packages are going to be installed:
  kernel-desktop-3.11.10-7.1 openstack-neutron openstack-neutron-openvswitch-agent openstack-suse-sudo openvswitch 
  openvswitch-kmp-desktop openvswitch-switch python-jsonrpclib python-neutron python-oslo.rootwrap 

and neither get these for the other command.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-05-07 19:38:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
avoid installation of unnecessary packages with zypper

zypper install --no-recommends should be used to avoid the installation
of unnecessary packages like CoudhDB or MongoDB when installing the
OpenStack packages.

Change-Id: Ie0b999476018ec3c06040f72412bedb5b3b2c7f8

commit_message:
Allow the default value of 1 to  be set for boot multiple

Allow one to call the following with their default values of 1:
* nova boot --num-instances 1
* nova boot --min-count 1
* nova boot --max-count 1

Don't allow min_count>max_count.

This is the only place where if a user passes in the default value the
CLI will return an error.

Change-Id: I805b3f0c778e9c70c5817624fb696a746dfe3d5b

commit_message:
Deprecate num-instances in favor of min/max count

For 'nova boot', num_instances only set max_count, which will try to
launch up to max_count instances. But sometimes users want to either
launch min_count instances or nothing. So deprecate --num-instances
and use --min-count and --max-count instead.

DocImpact: deprecate '--num-instances' for 'nova boot'

Change-Id: If0088aef554a528258799b22c6e793541474cb0d
Closes-bug: #1309244

commit_message:
Disable reports for puppet apply

That would shorten the deployment a bit.
The previous attempt was done in
"c5331a0 - Dmitry Ilyin, 9 months ago :
Disable puppet reports causing agent hangs"
but was lost while moving to the masterless
mode.

Closes-bug: #1281162

Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Apply conventions for Swift and Ceilometer

Use "swift" instead of "Swift".
Use "Telemetry" instead of "Ceilometer" where appropriate, lowercase
"ceilometer" as project name.
Reformat file common/section_objectstorage-features.xml.
Add some systemitem markup.

Partial-Bug: #1217503

Change-Id: Ia56a245a4993e4ea92fe19f38af443cf1bc411f5

lonut, for this patch the solution is to check the vmware_host_password attribute, if it is not set (the value is nil), I will use the databag.

For another patch in common code (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/92275/), I want to provide another solution: add new param to let us can specify the password when develop mode is true instead of return the index directly, this will make the code change in block-storage more simple, it will be like following:

vmware_host_pass = get_secret(node['openstack']['block-storage']['vmware']['secret_name'], node['openstack']['block-storage']['vmware']['vmware_host_password'])

Whatever, I think for currently this patch were already address Mark and your comments. David, I believe what Ionut is asking is why do we need the password attribute at all if we're going to use datbags in production?  It's fairly standard across the cookbooks now to use databags for all passwords, not attributes.   And for dev mode/testing, get_secret already handles that.   So, while I don't mind what you've done in your last patch, I have to agree with Ionut in that this should be just another password in a databag like all the rest."}, {'account_id': 2340, 'date': '2014-05-07 08:58:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

Right, let's remove the attribute in favor of storing the password in the databag."}, {'account_id': 6526, 'date': '2014-05-07 09:31:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

The problem is, if the develop mode is true, we can not assume the vCenter password is the secret_name since it is out of our OpenStack cookbook control. It's why I have another proposal in the common code to provide a new param for the get_secret method."}, {'account_id': 6526, 'date': '2014-05-07 09:45:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Let me make it more clear.

I agree with u we save all the password into databag.

But for the get_secret in common code, when we use develop mode, the get_secret return the index name as the password, that is fine for openstack user and db since they are created by cookbooks, but this assumption will not work for any external existing system for example the existing vCenter.'}, {'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2014-05-07 15:30:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

David, thx for the explaination.  Since dev mode is kinda a hack anyway, how about just using a dev mode specific attribute branch for this?   Something like:
if devmode
   if devmode['secret'][index]
       return devmode-['secret'][index]
   else return index

This way anybody can take advantage of this with any password and no recipe code changes are required?"}, {'account_id': 6526, 'date': '2014-05-08 01:51:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Do you mean we can use the node['openstack']['secret'][index] to save the password? for example:

node['openstack']['secret']['openstack_vmware_secret_name'] = '123456'

IMHO, it is a little hidden magic I think, but anyway I can try it and add more doc for this.

Anyone else has more suggestion?"}, {'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2014-05-08 14:33:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Get the vCenter password from databag for cinder

1. Add new attribute openstack_vmware_secret_name to indicate the
databag secret key
2. Get the password from databag if dev mode is false
3. Update the test cases

Implements: blueprint vmware-password-databag

Change-Id: Id6872d38c255067a4991aceaa0bf6fb400cce1c8

subject: Get the vCenter password from databag for compute

commit_message:
Get the vCenter password from databag for compute

1. Add new attribute openstack_vmware_secret_name to indicate the
databag secret key
2. Get the password from databag if dev mode is false
3. Update the test cases

Implements: blueprint vmware-password-databag

Change-Id: I342e26aee713216f2aecc39113a67ada25ec1fb5

commit_message:
Enable instance_name_template configuration

Sometimes the customer want to configure instance name basing on
their own format. So the 'instance_name_template' property should
support to be modified.

Change-Id: I39022c441fdeaf26faee8295dd8719c17dcc03a5

commit_message:
Run cinder-manage as correct user/group

We need to explicitly run cinder-manage with cinder user/group.
Running as root may cause files in /var/log/cinder/* to be owned by
root, and this will cause cinder services from being able to start (due
to being unable to write to files in that directory).

This is a non-issue when you install from packages as the package
post-install typically does a cinder-manage with the correct user, and
this ensures logs are created w/ correct ownership.

Change-Id: I50c94646a993ae5eb2e8775d979a4c0a73f2f4f2

commit_message:
Get the vCenter password from databag for glance


1. Add new attribute openstack_vmware_secret_name to indicate the
databag secret key
2. Get the password from databag if dev mode is false
3. Update the test cases

Implements: blueprint vmware-password-databag

Change-Id: I72f538a16d77cba9c1be9f32e0b37d1ee68e3bbc

commit_message:
Metaclass Python 3.x Compatibility

According to the OpenStack style guide (http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/), for Python 3.x compatibility use "six.add_metaclass" instead of " __metaclass__."

Change-Id: Ic7733a22294ecad30d185851d4f550f1386581fc

commit_message:
Run heat-manage as correct user/group

We need to explicitly run heat-manage with heat user/group.
Running as root may cause files in /var/log/heat/* to be owned by
root, and this will cause heat services from being able to start (due
to being unable to write to files in that directory).
This is a non-issue when you install from packages as the package
post-install typically does a heat-manage with the correct user, and
this ensures logs are created w/ correct ownership.

Change-Id: I6aede4f2b768cb191527ec27b0c8132c0582ebf2

commit_message:
Disable some murano tests

For this release murano support
deployment only of linux services, so we need to disable
deployment other ones as iis, sql etc
In case if we add RHEL tag those test will never be discavered
because RHEL and murano and heat always return false

Change-Id: If8b66a6145c7643d7c5ab3118e18e720f7f67080

commit_message:
add possibility of using public_urls for benchmarking

Add 'use_public_urls' option to the deployment config
This option will be used later for switching access method to the cloud.
Because in some use-cases cloud may be accessible only by public endpoints.

Add 'admin_port' option to the deployment config
This option defines administrative keystone port on the public network.

Closes-Bug: #1306448

Change-Id: Ifb838c5fe9eab5e81353d697aa747bd8adf77572

commit_message:
Fix cleanup for sahara

cleanup for sahara test data was never invoke.
It verified for deployment tag savanna, that was changed
everywehere.
So modification of deployment tag from savana to
sahara should fix the problem

Change-Id: I31662d70763af99631a60e889dfcabb80dada96b
Closes-Bug: #1318594

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

Change code in wsgi.py.

Before:
if not is_dict(body[entity_name]):
    return False
return True

commit_message:
Code Improvement

Change code in wsgi.py.

Before:
if not is_dict(body[entity_name]):
    return False
return True

After:
return is_dict(body[entity_name])

Since this calling is in the end of the method I
can just return the result of the calling.

Change-Id: I834f26aa5a91abd18b8da10aef81f3aeb72a61ed

commit_message:
Fix logrotation for fuel master node and its docker containers

* Split rsyslog client and server roles for openstack::logrotate
  class as well
* Add missed audit logs to rotation
* Fix template used for hourly logrotate job check
  (was 10-fuel*, now is 20-fuel*)
* Use common template for rsyslog server role both for host OS
  and rsylog container
  * Configure logrotate class also for host-only.pp
* Ensure postrotate for rsyslog in docker container case as well:
  * Issue HUPing for all rsyslog pids including ones in the docker
  containers, if any.

Closes-bug: #1316957

Change-Id: I76cabf2c1361836be55551cb5b4cbdc50c4a03ec
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix credentials passed to tempest

Tempest auth Manager recently changed to enforce the use of
Credentials objects in its public interface. Change lets tempest
take the CONF.identity defaults and decide how best to authorize.

Change-Id: If116d8cef145c310bd3a7077b3ae9780e705dc89
Closes-Bug: 1317549

commit_message:
Allow AgentExceptions to be logged properly

Remove the special handling in AgentException so that
the default Exception behavior is used when logging, and
details are shown.

Partially implements blueprint improve-engine-logging
Closes-Bug: #1316360
Change-Id: I9730c3e0733f1d6e7d1e40a03aea8499c9605093

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

commit_message:
V1.1 Functional Tests
Added tests for new V1.1 functions like pop and shard
Updated existing tests for V1.1 return calls
Added new json schemas
Edited functional test base to support multiple schemas

Implements: blueprint api-v1.1-functional-tests

Change-Id: I47f78461a42ae6e451eda759b3076ebc42d673e0

commit_message:
Rewrite base Class for sahara tests

Sahara clean_up methods and tearDown corrected
to properly remove data after run tests.
Fixed create nodegroup_templates and cluster_templates
for correctly work with/without autoassignment floating IP's.

Change-Id: I66922eee3d99e2754e089d01222c6053ed795347
Closes-Bug: #1311059
Closes-Bug: #1311554

commit_message:
Bump python-keystoneclient to >= 0.8.0

Starting from python-keystoneclient 0.8.0, the preferred way to
specify authN and identity endpoints is by using auth_uri and
identity_uri settings.  Otherwise, warnings are issued. To be able to
migrate to brand new world, we need to bump to the new version where
these settings were introduced.

Change-Id: Icbb9c3af9110e405d8b44bda529ccf1b3c1ae3a0

commit_message:
Set endpoint explicitly in keystone-client

On some deployments if endpoint is not set then keystone-client
incorrectly determines it. E.g. it uses internalURL instead of publicURL.

Closes: bug 1243273

Change-Id: I43fe9f5c89633fc2421a40218571338c68e8fad0

commit_message:
Do not allow bad keys while updating quota

Raise 400 (bad request) error instead of 200 (ok) if bad keys
are passed to the update quota request

Closes-Bug: #1248815
(cherry picked from commit 0d91b1a86a211610f78ac5c0df5a0b02b5a2f3a1)
Change-Id: Iaefaa4961dd3783dfab15f843cbb2dcb12195a7d

commit_message:
Create volume fail when image id is ""

When call create volume api with image id "", it will create an empty
volume.
But when create volume with snapshot id "" or srv volume "", it will
return an 404 error.
So it should create volume fail when call create volume api with image id
"".

Closes-Bug: #1302609
(cherry picked from commit eacab523be3d8f2f97809c785dba98e5e2e75c7b)
Change-Id: If2c7b061753bbbd172a09d35b343e73e90a1b7b4

[{'created': '2014-03-27 01:06:04.000000000', 'message': "VolumeManager: initialize even if a volume can't be found

If a previously volume cannot be exported (for example, because
an iSCSI target's backing LV is no longer present), VolumeManager
would previously bail out, leaving the volume service uninitialized.
This left volumes dangling in limbo: their state would be reported
as available (clearly not a reflection of reality), and they could
not be deleted (because the volume service that would be responsible
for deletion was unavailable).

Instead, catch an exception raised by ensure_export() separately,
log it, and set the volume to the error state.

For the tgt backend, this will also remove the volume_path file.
Previously this would cause an ISCSITargetRemoveFailed exception
when the volume would be removed. Instead, simply log a warning
and return, the way other backends (example: RBD) already do.

Also, add an info message that reflects the actual path and
contents of the volume_path file.

Finally, fix up the tgtadm unit test so that it tests for
identical IQNs,

Closes-bug: 1270959.
(cherry picked from commit d386210bc776a599bb31553c96e2a8a43acac61d)
Change-Id: Id61407c9a5e020d5a823dd7b8c973d237c35cb9b

commit_message:
VolumeManager: initialize even if a volume can't be found

If a previously volume cannot be exported (for example, because
an iSCSI target's backing LV is no longer present), VolumeManager
would previously bail out, leaving the volume service uninitialized.
This left volumes dangling in limbo: their state would be reported
as available (clearly not a reflection of reality), and they could
not be deleted (because the volume service that would be responsible
for deletion was unavailable).

Instead, catch an exception raised by ensure_export() separately,
log it, and set the volume to the error state.

For the tgt backend, this will also remove the volume_path file.
Previously this would cause an ISCSITargetRemoveFailed exception
when the volume would be removed. Instead, simply log a warning
and return, the way other backends (example: RBD) already do.

Also, add an info message that reflects the actual path and
contents of the volume_path file.

Finally, fix up the tgtadm unit test so that it tests for
identical IQNs,

Closes-bug: 1270959.
(cherry picked from commit d386210bc776a599bb31553c96e2a8a43acac61d)
Change-Id: Id61407c9a5e020d5a823dd7b8c973d237c35cb9b

commit_message:
Can't force-create snapshot by an non-exist error volume

If we create an LVM volume whose size larger than
rest space in VG, the volume would not exist with
error status.
But then we still can force create a snapshot
by this volume, and the snapshot's status is available.
In the code,I found in create_lv_snapshot,
it return False when fail to get the volume.
However, raising an exception is only way to be
handle outside.
So, we should raise exception instead of return False.

Closes-Bug: #1283338
(cherry picked from commit 379273925517e8b9bf971e018a1dc41f809c4814)
Change-Id: I80256f19d66da460c95ff23834abb79a557763bf

subject: LVM: Robustify skipactivation detection

Running lvchange might fail due to not being in
$PATH for non-root user, and the corresponding OSError
was not caught.

Simply check for lvm2 being 2.02.99 or newer.

Closes-Bug: #1269445
Change-Id: I308bd97cb729e83677f18a693274265a182d794c
(cherry picked from commit 193096a476ca3da2ef7f36f89fdbd897c5bcc320)
'}]
commit_message:
LVM: Robustify skipactivation detection

Running lvchange might fail due to not being in
$PATH for non-root user, and the corresponding OSError
was not caught.

Simply check for lvm2 being 2.02.99 or newer.

Closes-Bug: #1269445
Change-Id: I308bd97cb729e83677f18a693274265a182d794c
(cherry picked from commit 193096a476ca3da2ef7f36f89fdbd897c5bcc320)

commit_message:
Ensure glance-manage commands are run as correct user/group

Whilst testing stackforge cookbooks w/ ctracey's
cookbook-openstack-omnibus cookbook, I noticed that
/var/log/glance/glance-api.log was getting created as root and this
prevented glance-api from starting as it could not write to the log.

This is a non-issue when using packages as on Ubuntu (at least)
glance-manage db_sync is executed as part of glance-registry's
post-install script as user glance which ensures log file is created
with appropriate ownership.

Change-Id: I56d3e8caa68a32e34baa628a87c5e41b49602c59
Closes-Bug: #1317493

commit_message:
Added Trove (database) version API tests

Added a new file "test_versions.py" to verify the current
version of the Database API.  Required supporting
functions are added in a new client file "versions_client.py"
under the JSON interface.
Modified api/base.py, etc/tempest.conf.sample, clients.py and
config.py files

Partially implements blueprint: trove-tempest

commit_message:
Prepare for enabling H302 rule(data_processing, v3, volumes)

Currently H302 rule is ignored by tox. However, this rule should
be enabled. This patch partially fixes this problem to prepare for
H302 rule.

Change-Id: Ia25c982c57e059b73c36c1db209b26a8f958f7eb

subject: Prepare for enabling H302 rule(api/{n*,o*,t*})

commit_message:
Prepare for enabling H302 rule(api/{n*,o*,t*})

Currently H302 rule is ignored by tox. However, this rule should
be enabled. This patch partially fixes this problem to prepare for
H302 rule.

[{'created': '2014-05-09 04:21:03.000000000', 'message': "Use X-Backend-Storage-Policy-Index

The reconciler adds a number of X-Backend headers to container
responses and also override InternalClient requests which over-ride
container_info when setting X-Backend-Storage-Policy-Index.  Since
only backend requests will ever refer to policy by index, this change
unifies this backend request header with the other headers already
prefixed by Backend.  It also superficially simplifies the proxy's
BaseController translation of policy_index to name since X-Backend
headers are already stripped from outgoing requests.

Change-Id: I7597dac2bde7fc438c96b20e1574508aba5cfa05
"}]
commit_message:
Use X-Backend-Storage-Policy-Index

The reconciler adds a number of X-Backend headers to container
responses and also override InternalClient requests which over-ride
container_info when setting X-Backend-Storage-Policy-Index.  Since
only backend requests will ever refer to policy by index, this change
unifies this backend request header with the other headers already
prefixed by Backend.  It also superficially simplifies the proxy's
BaseController translation of policy_index to name since X-Backend
headers are already stripped from outgoing requests.

Change-Id: I7597dac2bde7fc438c96b20e1574508aba5cfa05

commit_message:
Fix defaults in the endpoint manager

The create method of the EndpointManager class of the client is missing
defaults for the region, adminurl and internalurl parameters, unlike the
endpoint-create command of the CLI.

The client should be changed to use the same defaults as the CLI.

Closes-Bug: #1318436
Change-Id: If101ee4904d524a249e73df392c6a1e07cae24b2

commit_message:
Checkout stable/icehouse of OpenStack

From the stable/icehouse branch of tripleo-incubator we need to set
DIB_REPOREF_* variables for all of the OpenStack projects to
stable/icehouse.

Change-Id: I59cac05615780c702234730c64e4127876602947

commit_message:
Add os-cloud-config to global requirements

TripleO is in the process of moving scripts out of incubator and
into os-cloud-config, so add it to global requirements and projects
so that it can be utilised.

Change-Id: If44ca7f0f11a5ec05bcc57bde7b05403fbb6e1fa

Changes for Fedora log layout

A few changes for the log layout on Fedora; mostly different paths and
adding a few checks before assuming files exist.

is a slightly different format from ISO8601 in that the date isn't
separated from the time using 'T'.

(However, note that the iso8601 library happily accepts this format)

Add a specific regexp for this format so we can test for it in the
places we know it is used. This also means we can remove the generic
%(timestamp)s regexp.

Note that unlike the isotime and strtime formats, whether this format
includes timezone or microsecond information depends on whether the
datetime object had those fields set. The isotime format always
includes a timezone but not microseconds, whereas the strtime format
never includes a timezone but always includes microseconds.

There are a small number of examples where this format is used in JSON
too - e.g. the instance usage audit log extension pre-serializes its
timestamps by doing:

                    period_ending=str(end),

Using a name like 'xmltime' for the timestamp format used in cases
like this actually makes sense - it highlights that the format used
in this case is a weird mistake.

Full context here:

  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-April/033971.html

commit_message:
Add specific regexp for timestamps in v2 xml

datetime objects are serialized into xml using simply str() and this
is a slightly different format from ISO8601 in that the date isn't
separated from the time using 'T'.

(However, note that the iso8601 library happily accepts this format)

Add a specific regexp for this format so we can test for it in the
places we know it is used. This also means we can remove the generic
%(timestamp)s regexp.

Note that unlike the isotime and strtime formats, whether this format
includes timezone or microsecond information depends on whether the
datetime object had those fields set. The isotime format always
includes a timezone but not microseconds, whereas the strtime format
never includes a timezone but always includes microseconds.

There are a small number of examples where this format is used in JSON
too - e.g. the instance usage audit log extension pre-serializes its
timestamps by doing:

        return dict(period_beginning=str(begin),
                    period_ending=str(end),

Using a name like 'xmltime' for the timestamp format used in cases
like this actually makes sense - it highlights that the format used
in this case is a weird mistake.

Full context here:

  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-April/033971.html

Change-Id: I70f839ac17273ed10078b833aeba308bd5e994e1

The create method of the EndpointManager class of the client is missing
defaults for the region, adminurl and internalurl parameters, unlike the
endpoint-create command of the CLI.

The client should be changed to use the same defaults as the CLI.

Change-Id: I3262cfd101671b045ae7413b20e795567b47f545
Closes-Bug: #1318436
'}]
commit_message:
Missing Defaults in Method in the Identity Python Client

The create method of the EndpointManager class of the client is missing
defaults for the region, adminurl and internalurl parameters, unlike the
endpoint-create command of the CLI.

The client should be changed to use the same defaults as the CLI.

Change-Id: I3262cfd101671b045ae7413b20e795567b47f545
Closes-Bug: #1318436

commit_message:
Missing Defaults in Method in the Identity Python Client

The create method in the EndpointManager class of the client is missing
defaults for the region, adminurl and internalurl parameters, unlike the
endpoint-create command of the CLI.

The client should be changed to use the same defaults as the CLI.

Change-Id: I0c3a3197bd6df0a6b0dc63635045678f20881645
Closes-Bug: #1318436

commit_message:
eliminate the need for hp3parclient in tests

In order to eliminate the need to have the hp3parclient in the
global-requirements project, we need to remove the hp3parclient
from being imported in all 3par driver unit tests in cinder.

Closes-Bug: #1315195
Change-Id: Ife5c70871e742be5970be8f0284e12554f93cab4

commit_message:
Adds link for KVM-KSM

Adds link to KVM: Kernel Samepage Merging
to link section at end of chatper 40 (ch051).
No link added for XEN-TPS as this section of
chapter 40 needs further review - new bug to follow.

Made edits for clarity (diane fleming)

Change-Id: Ieeb5f83260120cb66238adc5338955d5fbc59dce
Closes-Bug: #1317853

commit_message:
VMware: prevent image snapshot if no root disk defined

If there is no root disk defined then the snapshot should
throw an exception.

Change-Id: I0549b8ca9ba41b734277600cb66a74b27ca72d88

commit_message:
Updated cinder tables for the config-ref

We missed some updates with the late switch to oslo.messaging in cinder.
This patch imports the updated defaults and help strings.

Change-Id: I8b01227ee536ac28f0efb84c02e10239cdaf937e
Backport: icehouse
(cherry picked from commit 4d83b36bd19f63ca0ca6b9b8f97b9face3e10128)

commit_message:
ValueError when cookie pagesize is empty string

If a user somehow gets the value of 'horizon_pagesize' set to "", the
method horizon.utils.functions.get_page_size will raise a ValueError
because it can't convert the empty string to an int. Clearly this would
also happen if the value gets set to any other non-valid int-literal.

Change-Id: I4b1dd07df75d931f8c61823c93c5dd6ecc145686
Closes-Bug: 1316331

commit_message:
Don't use a common file

The common.py file is only used by autohelp.py, so is not really a
common file. Include its content in autohelp.py.

Also remove the unused _() definition.

Change-Id: I4e228637e3f6287fd2770ba386dd0fdba6977a81

commit_message:
Clean up openstack-common.conf

oslo-incubator will introduce new integrity check in [1].
That will help developer find inconsistent issue while copying
from oslo-incubator. The check just outputs warnings. These are
changes according to warning:
 * sort the modules in openstack-common.conf
 * Fix wrong module names

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/76901/

Change-Id: Ie939d46a72732357acc9dab03c0682b0e271a7ed
Related-Bug: #1295582

commit_message:
Pass configured auth strategy to neutronclient

When the token is invalid Nova emits a log trace about an
unknown auth strategy (caused by neutron client). This is a
red herring and is only masking the fact that the token was
unable to be validated in the first place.

Partial-bug: 1297309

Change-Id: Ia3801f80c7ca18674fcf46b5270aa04f6c8c9331
(cherry picked from commit fdd689c146713d18eb901d6f3ec986cdd11d13fe)

commit_message:
Make sure leases are maintained until release

Dnsmasq asks nova-dhcpbridge for existing leases on reboot, but
we don't return addresses that have been deallocated but not yet
released. This modifies nova to return leased but not allocated
addresses. It also delays removing the vif until we disassociate
the ip so we still have access to the mac address.

Resolves-bug: 1300355

Change-Id: Id78d66aad5005f052a1b49002de0ef13ef5a298d

commit_message:
libvirt: optimize pause mode support

Commit bfb28fcf9031af4c695177663702ce05edbbfa4d added a method
call that checks if the libvirt driver support the
VIR_DOMAIN_START_PAUSED flag. This patch optimizes that by reading
the value at startup.

Change-Id: I0fc1edec55df609ab25b9999f4a0d077ddcf0be7

commit_message:
Remove quota-class logic from context and make unit tests pass

Continuation of quota-class removal started in
I1110022d6f628d03aaf363da707f2d2ef1600437.

Since we don't have an API to set quota-class any more, we don't need to
store it inside of the context. Also begin removing quota-class logic from
nova.quota to make test_quota pass with changes to context

Change-Id: I85dd24121a434b95dc6f0af180444d4258b50765

commit_message:
Support multi-version pydevd

We need to support multi-version pydevd
in order to supporting pycharm3 and pydev3 remote debug.
If we want to remote debug by pydev3 or pycharm3,
"from pydev import pydev" is not work,
need to "import pydevd" directly.

Change-Id: I975c859c46f81d7fe1ca3dfebe05040153471800

commit_message:
Delete in-process snapshot when deleting instance

Try to delete the image created to hold the snapshot when the snapshot
creation fails because either the instance doesn't exist or it is in the
deleting task_state.

Closes-Bug: #1296590
Change-Id: I422c4f10c348d189fee217b55e0766e73eb5b16c

commit_message:
Add a docstring to hacking unit tests

This commit adds a docstring to the hacking check unit tests
explaining how the tests work. To someone who isn't well versed with
how pep8/flake8 works the tests cases are a bit of black magic.

Change-Id: I5dc61612a5fec42443d8d89eaf700bb17b4b0842

commit_message:
XenAPI: Remove unneeded instance argument from image downloading

The Xenapi image downloading code requires an instance argument
when launching a VM.  However, the downloading code doesn't
need the instance information as it doesn't use it for
any processing/debugging/loging.  We can remove this
argument safely.

Change-Id: Id8b531b74e5f0e59638b608bff93fc89b66b889d
Closes-bug: #1307662

commit_message:
VMWare: spawn refactor - phase 1 - create_virtual_disk

Several methods are repeating code for creating the virtual disk.
This refactor isolates the code for that task so it can be reused.

partial blueprint improve-vmware-disk-usage
partial blueprint vmware-spawn-refactor
Co-authored-by: Maithem <munshedm@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Tracy Jones <tjones@vmware.com>

Change-Id: If764340be76abbb24e1954f02b3ecb317ba143f9

Agree with Michael about the name of that state parameter, it's a bit awkward, should rename that to power_on or something like that so it's more clear.

@Tracy, responding to:

"spawn(power_on=False) and unrescue (power_on=false) are both tested as part of the rescue and destroy driver methods. Can we add tests for spawn and rescue in test_vmops in a subsequent patch in order to move this patch set along??"

First, I realize now why you changed the driver API to pass in the power_on flag for spawn and unrescue, but that's not right and it leads to another issue, which is we're testing this in the wrong spot essentially.  We're testing the driver and mocking out vmops for the driver tests.  It's all well and good to test the driver calls vmops properly, but we shouldn't rely on testing vmops from the driver, because it's not isolated and as I've said before, if the driver code changes to not use those vmops methods then the vmops methods are no longer tested.  So we should really also have isolated tests in test_vmops for spawn/unrescue, at least for the power_on=False cases.  I think this is symptomatic of a test approach that's been propagated in the vmware driver for too long, that is there are several tests at the high level which stub things out to test permutations at the low-level, which is not proper unit testing.

For example, if we have a call chain of A->B->C and we're only testing C via calls to A, that's broken.  We should test each layer individually, and that's a big reason why we're doing this refactor - to break out nested methods so they can be tested in isolation.

So in this example, A is the driver, B is vmops, and C is the vm_utils power_on_instance method.  We should have separate tests for each.  The vmops tests stub out vm_utils, and the driver tests stub out vmops.  The layers are black boxes in that way and can be modified independently without having to fix the entire test stack because of a change at the bottom layer.  That just adds to maintenance costs.

And finally, "Can we add tests for spawn and rescue in test_vmops in a subsequent patch in order to move this patch set along?" - no, we can't. I've been in too many vmware patches like this where it goes on and on because the main point is being missed and finally everyone is exhausted and wants to move on so we all agree to just push it to another review later, but by that time I'm at least personally burned out and don't want to review the other patch spun off from the original one.  We need to get this right in this patch before moving on, otherwise there isn't a point in doing this work.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-05-06 14:50:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 59: Code-Review-1

I agree with Matt.

Tracy (et al), we very much appreciate you all prioritizing this work, and allocating lots of effort to getting these done. However, we've been through a lot of iterations on these for reasons other than us just being pedantic. I think we should definitely avoid merging this and any other patch simply because we're sick of it.

The point of this series is to (among other things) make the driver more testable. Let us not lose sight of that goal and make sure that we're *actually* raising the quality bar and not just moving code around."}, {'account_id': 8027, 'date': '2014-05-07 00:59:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 60.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-07 00:59:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 60:

@Matt:

- Changing the driver api signature in patch 58 was not correct indeed. Patch 59 essentially reverted that.

- the refactored function in vm_util.py now has isolated unit test for it.

- It is true test_driver_api.py having lots of tests that exercises vmop.py via making calls to driver.py methods. Most of the driver.py calls that uses vmops.py are essentially straight passthrough to vmops.py calls of the same name (often with exact same set of parameters). Those tests would have exercised vmops.py identically had self.conn.X been replaced with self.conn._vmops.X. This is essentially what I have done with this patch for the tests affected by this refactor. (We should look into moving these tests to test_vmops.py later as well)

- After changes like the above, there is a need for a new, fairly trivial set of tests in test_driver.py to validate the passthrough behavior (A->B). I think it makes sense to do that driver-wide in a separate patch.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-07 02:07:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 60: Verified+1

commit_message:
VMware: spawn refactor - phase 1 - power_on_vm

move power_on to vm_util and change all power_on in vmops to use it

ensure test_driver_api tests only the driver and not vmops

change id for the last review in this phase 1 series with a spawn
test is Ia137f1ea4b9fa43741cdd7d610831da8e5474d62

partial blueprint vmware-spawn-refactor

Change-Id: I5c1d8bc38c4a7d0107c8d7639e385239e53b070d

commit_message:
Pretty print JSON sample files and remove unused files

Pretty print JSON samples to follow JSON formatting conventions.

Replace JSON and XML files with reference to api-site, so that we only
have one place with these files.

Remove unused JSON and XML sample files.

Co-Autored-By: Diane Fleming <diane.fleming@rackspace.com>

Partial-Bug: #1217503

Change-Id: If7b98a321b373d183859ba1ebce5cdd131b43161

commit_message:
Get credential IDs from Credentials class

With the move to Credentials class, tenant_id and user_id are
available in the Credentials instance.
Several test use identity admin client to obtain tenant_id
and user_id, fixing them to get the IDs from Credentials instead.

Partially implements: bp multi-keystone-api-version-tests

Change-Id: I8c38fb8d191a88fab37633c6edffd54492c41fd5

commit_message:
remove libvirt work around

libvirt in precise-updates now has the fix that we need (released
on March 20th), so we should no longer have to have a local work
around for it.

Change-Id: Id094a7e3e3004acd3d47b7fe34161ed2995e095b

commit_message:
Remove tempest_auto_config script

This script isn't being used by anyone to my knowledge nor has it
really been maintained since it was first added. We will be working
on a plan for automating tempest configuration soon and this
doesn't really fit the initial set requirements of requirements. It
also does not have any testing, so I expect that it has bit rotted
and probably doesn't work anymore.

Change-Id: Id896d9877312dfb6b12b54ea1c598a1940cdd9ce

commit_message:
Adding RHEL support for puppet-sahara

Adding a section to install for redhat-based
systems.
* adding require mysql::server
* adding sahara-api-redhat.erb template
* adding section to install that uses the new
  template to build an init.d script
* updates for compatibility with latest versions
  of puppet modules
  

Change-Id: Idecde095040cf2ed31f81ac058aed526224aa73e
Closes-Bug:  bug 1295342

commit_message:
Update tool chain setup

Adjust doc-test.conf for publishing to havana branch.
Require recent openstack-doc-tools version.
Invoke openstack-doc-test with --publish option, no need to remove www
directory afterwards. Also, enable verbose output.

Change-Id: Icce48c071d9eafca9ab3de5d4ceb0a528398b422

[{'created': '2014-03-20 23:44:52.000000000', 'message': "stack.sh fails for Cisco plugin with missing cisco_plugins.ini error

When the Cisco Nexus monolithic plugin is configured in the localrc,
stack.sh fails with the error message:
     sed: can't read /etc/neutron/plugins/cisco/cisco_plugins.ini:
          No such file or directory

This failure was introduced with the merge of change set 76992
(bug #1285884). Change set 76992 removed the copying of
Q_PLUGIN_EXTRA_CONF_FILES from the neutron project area to directories
under /etc/neutron. This copy from neutron to /etc is required by the
Cisco Nexus monolithic plugin, since this plugin follows the original
model for generating extra config files based on localrc settings:
 - Copy default config file(s) from neutron project to /etc using
   a relative path (relative to neutron and relative to /)
 - Modify the copies of the config file(s) using localrc settings
 - Add a --config-file command line setting for neutron server which
   points to the modified config file(s) under /etc

The fix is to add the copying of the default versions of the extra
config files from neutron to /etc into the cisco devstack script.

Change-Id: Ifbae197ed591f7cccfd6d51eae2b21e31eb0a409
Closes-Bug: #1295411
"}]
commit_message:
stack.sh fails for Cisco plugin with missing cisco_plugins.ini error

When the Cisco Nexus monolithic plugin is configured in the localrc,
stack.sh fails with the error message:
     sed: can't read /etc/neutron/plugins/cisco/cisco_plugins.ini:
          No such file or directory

This failure was introduced with the merge of change set 76992
(bug #1285884). Change set 76992 removed the copying of
Q_PLUGIN_EXTRA_CONF_FILES from the neutron project area to directories
under /etc/neutron. This copy from neutron to /etc is required by the
Cisco Nexus monolithic plugin, since this plugin follows the original
model for generating extra config files based on localrc settings:
 - Copy default config file(s) from neutron project to /etc using
   a relative path (relative to neutron and relative to /)
 - Modify the copies of the config file(s) using localrc settings
 - Add a --config-file command line setting for neutron server which
   points to the modified config file(s) under /etc

The fix is to add the copying of the default versions of the extra
config files from neutron to /etc into the cisco devstack script.

Change-Id: Ifbae197ed591f7cccfd6d51eae2b21e31eb0a409
Closes-Bug: #1295411

commit_message:
Share Certificates API's tests between V2 & V3

There is a lot of copy&paste test code for Nova v2/v3 API tests.
In addition, we need to add many checks for API test coverage.
As the result, we should apply the same changes to v2 and v3 tests.

This patch reuse the test code of V2 and V3 Certificates APIs
Inheriting the V2 Certificates API's test from V3 tests.
Also removing the status code check which is different between
V2 & V3. Status code has been validated at client side.

Partially implements blueprint nova-api-test-inheritance

Change-Id: I98e03cecdbd36e521d007bbfb92a5f9818ff28f6

[{'created': '2014-05-08 11:24:19.000000000', 'message': 'ML2 VxlanTypeDriver: Synchronize of VxlanAllocation table

At neutron startup VxlanTypeDriver syncs tunnel range from conf
to DB. In case multiple servers deployment restarting several
servers at the same time could lead to DB exceptions being thrown.
Need to synchronize between neutron servers by locking VxlanAllocation
table.

Change-Id: Idf9908f039070b9194612484603f592f1a8d74b8
Closes-Bug: #1307295
'}]
commit_message:
ML2 VxlanTypeDriver: Synchronize of VxlanAllocation table

At neutron startup VxlanTypeDriver syncs tunnel range from conf
to DB. In case multiple servers deployment restarting several
servers at the same time could lead to DB exceptions being thrown.
Need to synchronize between neutron servers by locking VxlanAllocation
table.

Change-Id: Idf9908f039070b9194612484603f592f1a8d74b8
Closes-Bug: #1307295

commit_message:
Add a zookeeper jobboard integration test

Test the base jobboard tests against a real
zookeeper server if one is available (if not
skip the tests).

commit_message:
Cleanup zookeeper integration testing

In the persistence tests only use zake when zookeeper is
not available (and of the right version). When zookeeper is
available skip running zake.

In the jobboard tests split out the tests which are not
specific for zake into a base class (allowing for a future
commit to add a zookeeper integration test).

Change-Id: I50d51639a7f6c03c29d559c485676fddb9a7cf20

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-10 03:06:00.000000000', 'message': 'Use a more stable flush method

Instead of using the zake provided flush method (which
does have issues, since it does not guarantee that the
associated watches will have been called) instead use a
new method which creates nodes, waits for there watches
to be triggered, does other work, and then deletes the
node and waits for that watcher to be triggered; this is
more stable (as it depends on the linearity guarantee
of zookeeper and the kazoo threading model).

Change-Id: I12fd9c7bcc5cd9009b4175166edfc924e94161bf
'}]
commit_message:
Use a more stable flush method

Instead of using the zake provided flush method (which
does have issues, since it does not guarantee that the
associated watches will have been called) instead use a
new method which creates nodes, waits for there watches
to be triggered, does other work, and then deletes the
node and waits for that watcher to be triggered; this is
more stable (as it depends on the linearity guarantee
of zookeeper and the kazoo threading model).

Change-Id: I12fd9c7bcc5cd9009b4175166edfc924e94161bf

The _clear method is only used in one place (in close) so the
benefit of it being a function is not really valueable so move
its logic to the close method itself.

Also fix that the job_watcher does not need to be reset since
it can now survive session lose/disconnection, setting it to

'}]
commit_message:
Remove the _clear method and do not reset the job_watcher

The _clear method is only used in one place (in close) so the
benefit of it being a function is not really valueable so move
its logic to the close method itself.

Also fix that the job_watcher does not need to be reset since
it can now survive session lose/disconnection, setting it to
none is not useful anymore and actually creates more watchers
that provide the same data (which is bad).

Change-Id: I243ec0551a341df74f478b0161ffd559a75278fe

commit_message:
Make plugin deallocation check optional

The fix for memory leakage in the related bug added a check for plugin
deallocation that performed a call to gc.collect() after every test.
This had the side-effect of increasing test execution time by ~50%, so
this patch makes the check optional via an environment variable
(OS_CHECK_PLUGIN_DEALLOCATION).

It may make sense to create a periodic job that runs with the check
enabled, but otherwise the check can be used by developers for
debugging purposes.

Change-Id: I9ebe663abbc4e4ff3a62d807d5a3230c2ecccd07
Related-Bug: #1234857

[{'created': '2014-03-25 15:50:29.000000000', 'message': "Provides ability to reference existing neutron resources

Additional properties 'network' and 'subnet' are added to
the resources (existing properties 'network_id' and
'subnet_id' are deprecated). 'network'  and 'subnet' can
now carry name or id. Pre-existing neutron resources
can now be referenced in heat templates by their name
and not necessarily by their UUID. This would help porting
templates across deployments.

commit_message:
Provides ability to reference existing neutron resources

Additional properties 'network' and 'subnet' are added to
the resources (existing properties 'network_id' and
'subnet_id' are deprecated). 'network'  and 'subnet' can
now carry name or id. Pre-existing neutron resources
can now be referenced in heat templates by their name
and not necessarily by their UUID. This would help porting
templates across deployments.

Change-Id: I644f5d6ee2e5ccabde190bd73eacc71daaf41f4d
Closes-Bug: #1286128

commit_message:
Change get to show

Update function names to use the word show instead of get,
so as to maintain subcommand consistency with the other projects.

Change-Id: I9ba3283966327d77d33ccd6b19d17e61d86580c0
Implements: blueprint change-get-to-show

commit_message:
Remove explicit dependency on amqplib

amqp (or amqplib) is only accessed via kombu, and kombu
already specifies the right dependency (either amqp if new
enough or amqplib for old versions of kombu).

Change-Id: I4efa419db1befdfcbe639a8557e21eb97ca3a26e

'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-04-24 13:37:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-04-25 16:30:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Do not merge

I think we're on the wrong track here. I've done a little poking around and we have a bunch of different formats in our API output: https://gist.github.com/markmc/11295100

we sometimes have timezone info in the form of 'Z' (for UTC) or +/-00:00 or even a non-UTC offset ... and sometimes we don't have any timezone info

sometimes we have a 'T' separating date from time, and sometimes we don't. The iso8601 format requires this even if the is08601 library makes it optional

and, finally, sometimes we have subsecond timestamp resolution and other times we don't

Personally, I'm thinking our default should be to (a) have everything in UTC timezone and indicate this with a trailing 'Z', (b) always include the 'T' separator and (c) only have subsecond time resolution where we think there's a real use case for it


Now ... this patch strips off the timezone and subsecond resolution, but only for the keypairs API. That's a totally random approach to cleaning this up.


IMHO, we should allow Ghanshyam merge his useful new unit test (i.e. If695a23cf95862b7bec6fbc5bdf7fc1733d08d4a) including a change to the timestamp regexp to allow the combination of timezone info and subsecond time resolution ... that combination really isn't any more weird than some of the other formats we currently use


This is something that should be properly cleaned up across Nova and I'm going to do a bit more digging into it ... but we shouldn't add an arbitrary workaround like this."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-04-25 17:49:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Mark,

It's pretty well-known that we have a thousand different time formats in the v2 API. It's something I've raised as an important thing for fixing in v3. Since we've moved to objects underneath, everything gained a timezone under the covers, and that has caused some of the stringified datetimes to *change* in the API response from what it has been in the past. This patch addresses that change/regression.

Unfortunately, unless we're going to break 80% of all of our API timestamps in v2 to become consistent, I think we're in for this kind of hunt-and-patch behavior. The benefit of moving this out to the helper method was specifically to allow further fixing for datetimes that are exposed like this that may have changed due to the internal plumbing changes."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-04-25 19:34:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Why do you say moving to objects changed the behavior and this fixes it?

Are you assuming keypair timestamps didn't previously include a timezone and subsecond resolution? What's that theory based on?"}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-04-29 14:08:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I've dug further and summarized my findings here: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-April/033971.html

The issue in If695a23cf95862b7bec6fbc5bdf7fc1733d08d4a that caused the need for this patch was just with the XML serialization. I don't think we should be adding hacks in the API layer just for XML serialization.

We use the 'strtime' format for the JSON serialization of these values and this format ignores the timezone information. IOW, the move to objects wouldn't have caused a change in the JSON output.

We use the 'str(datetime)' format for the XML serialization. These values would always have had microsecond information, but the port to objects is what added the timezone information. I don't see a big issue with timestamps in our XML serialization containing both microsecond and timezone information. Any XML API client (and we claim there aren't any) that cares about parsing the timestamps would already be handling microseconds *or* timezone, so I think it's highly unlikely they're not set up to parse both."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-04-30 16:04:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2014-05-10 02:20:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandon as per discussion.'}]
